John Ralston Saul delivers a lecture at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Alberta" title="University of Alberta">University of Alberta</a> on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2006-11-17"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="11-17"><a href="/wiki/November_17" title="November 17">November 17</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2006" title="2006">2006</a></span>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/John_Ralston_(disambiguation)" title="John Ralston (disambiguation)" class="mw-redirect">John Ralston (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><b>John Ralston Saul</b>, <a href="/wiki/Order_of_Canada" title="Order of Canada">CC</a> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1947-06-19"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="06-19"><a href="/wiki/June_19" title="June 19">June 19</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1947" title="1947">1947</a></span>) is a <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canadian</a> author and <a href="/wiki/Essayist" title="Essayist" class="mw-redirect">essayist</a>.</p>
<p>As an essayist, Saul is particularly known for his commentaries on the nature of <a href="/wiki/Individualism" title="Individualism">individualism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Citizenship" title="Citizenship">citizenship</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Public_good" title="Public good">public good</a>; the failures of manager-, or more precisely <a href="/wiki/Technocracy_(bureaucratic)" title="Technocracy (bureaucratic)">technocrat</a>-, led societies; the confusion between <a href="/wiki/Leadership" title="Leadership">leadership</a> and <a href="/wiki/Managerialism" title="Managerialism">managerialism</a>; <a href="/wiki/Military_strategy" title="Military strategy">military strategy</a>, in particular <a href="/wiki/Irregular_warfare" title="Irregular warfare" class="mw-redirect">irregular warfare</a>; the role of <a href="/wiki/Freedom_of_speech" title="Freedom of speech">freedom of speech</a> and culture; and his critique of contemporary economic arguments.</p>
